<subSubSection id="C32C6515FFF4FFDCA9A9FBE1153544B6" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B89369EFFF4FFDCA9A9FBE110034474" blockId="20.[189,310,1042,1068]" box="[189,310,1042,1068]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
<heading id="D0C181F2FFF4FFDCA9A9FBE110034474" bold="true" box="[189,310,1042,1068]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" reason="3">
<emphasis id="B942EA8CFFF4FFDCA9A9FBE110034474" bold="true" box="[189,310,1042,1068]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B89369EFFF4FFDCA9A9FBB1153544B6" blockId="20.[189,1399,1090,1263]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
Similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCA828FBB0108F4404" baseAuthorityName="Eichhorn" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[316,442,1090,1117]" class="Insecta" family="Adelgidae" genus="Adelges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merkeri">
<emphasis id="B942EA8CFFF4FFDCA828FBB0108F4404" box="[316,442,1090,1117]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
A. 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCA84BFBB1108F4404" box="[351,442,1090,1116]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="merkeri">merkeri</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but neosistens with central areas of wax pore plates on meso- and metathoracic spinal sclerites often more-or-less triangular, each with 3–6 pits. Total number of pits on 10 central areas 18–59, usually less than 40. The characters distinguishing 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCAAA3FB7F151044FD" baseAuthorityName="Ratzeburg" baseAuthorityYear="1843" box="[951,1061,1164,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Adelgidae" genus="Adelges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceae">
<emphasis id="B942EA8CFFF4FFDCAAA3FB7F151044FD" box="[951,1061,1164,1190]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
A. 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCAACCFB7F151044FD" box="[984,1061,1164,1189]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="piceae">piceae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCAD74FB7F15E944FD" baseAuthorityName="Eichhorn" baseAuthorityYear="1957" box="[1120,1244,1163,1190]" class="Insecta" family="Adelgidae" genus="Adelges" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="merkeri">
<emphasis id="B942EA8CFFF4FFDCAD74FB7F15E944FD" box="[1120,1244,1163,1190]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">
A. 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCAD95FB7815E944FD" box="[1153,1244,1163,1189]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="merkeri">merkeri</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are variable, and the identification requires several specimens (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA74B6FFFF4FFDCAA1DFB43150B4492" author="Blackman R. L. &amp; Eastop V. F." box="[777,1086,1200,1227]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref17847" refString="Blackman R. L. &amp; Eastop V. F. 2006. Aphids on the World's Herbaceous Plants and Shrubs (2 vols). Wiley, Chichester." type="book" year="2006">Blackman &amp; Eastop 2006</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA74B6FFFF4FFDCAD5FFB4315F04492" author="Heie O. E." box="[1099,1221,1200,1226]" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" refId="ref18680" refString="Heie O. E. 2004. Danmarks Fauna. Vols. 87 - 88: Bladlus 1 - 2. Dansk Naturhistorisk Forening, Copenhagen." type="book" year="2004">Heie 2004</bibRefCitation>
). Monoecious, anholocyclic on 
<taxonomicName id="4C364D1DFFF4FFDCA86BFB2610F544B7" box="[383,448,1237,1263]" class="Pinopsida" family="Pinaceae" genus="Abies" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Pinales" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B942EA8CFFF4FFDCA86BFB2610F544B7" box="[383,448,1237,1263]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="21">Abies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Found on trunk and branches. Not ant-attended.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
